The Southern Kaduna Christian Leaders Association has called on the federal government to immediately work out modalities for the payment of N50 billion compensation to Christians that lost their properties in the ongoing herdsmen mayhem in the State.  In a press statement signed and issued to Journalists in Kaduna yesterday through its national chairman, Bishop Simon Peters Mutum said the people of the zone has lost so much, hence the need for the government to pay compensation.  The chairman noted that there is a need for the establishment of IDP camps in the region, where victims of herder’s attacks would live and be taken care of.  According to him, Christians, who have been displaced from their homes, are in Zonkwa and other places based on the Christian spirit of good neighbourliness and the culture of family solidarity and care.  He further appealed to SEMA and NEMA should to assist the displaced Christians, mostly women and children with relief materials especially at these hard times.  He observed that there is a need for proper investigation into the incessant killings, stressing that a fact Finding Committee (FFC) should be inaugurated, with members comprising of people with proven integrity from both religions.  Mutum maintained that there is a deliberate delay or refusal to deploy security personnel to flash points and have refused to believe that government is overwhelmed by terrorist. The union observed that if government adhered to the advice, it would also complement the efforts of the Kaduna State Peace Commission in restoring normalcy in the country.